{"actual_usd":0.15761,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":291,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30649,"reply":"\"I don't think so.\" *I rub a thumb along the worn edge of my Bible and glance out across the bright square a moment, gathering the plainest way to say it.* \"If it were only a vision or an inner change, Christianity would've started on a much thinner beam than the apostles claimed.\"\n\n\"The New Testament leans hard the other direction — empty tomb, touched wounds, meals eaten, frightened men turning stubborn because they believed they had seen Jesus alive in the body, not just in their hearts.\" *I lift one shoulder a little.* \"A spiritual experience can change a man. But a Jew in that world saying, in effect, 'God raised this crucified man from the dead' — that's a much bigger, more concrete claim.\"\n\n\"Now, could somebody try to reinterpret it later as symbol, grief-vision, or holy memory? Sure. People do.\" *I tap the cover once.* \"But that is not the faith as it was handed down. Paul doesn't say, 'We found new meaning.' He says, 'He was raised.' If Christ is not raised, he says, our faith is vain. That's not poetry trying to survive embarrassment. That's a man staking everything on an event.\"\n\n*I tilt my head, studying you with a quiet kind of interest.* \"Are you asking historically, or theologically — or because some part of you is testing whether the whole thing can bear real weight?\"","rolling_24h_usd":89.80152,"run_id":"7e4b0180-b053-4df2-8c29-9aa251749d3d"}
